<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Tascam-16Track.jpg" class="image" title="The TASCAM 85 16B analog tape recorder can record 16 tracks of audio on 1 inch (2.54cm) tape."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Tascam-16Track.jpg/300px-Tascam-16Track.jpg" width="300" height="222" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Tascam-16Track.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/TASCAM" title="TASCAM">TASCAM</a> 85 16B analog tape recorder can record 16 tracks of audio on 1 inch (2.54cm) tape.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Multitrack recording</b> ('multitracking' or just 'tracking' for short) is a method of <a href="/wiki/Sound_recording" title="Sound recording" class="mw-redirect">sound recording</a> that allows for the separate recording of multiple sound sources to create a cohesive whole. This is the most common method of <a href="/wiki/Sound_recording_and_reproduction" title="Sound recording and reproduction">recording</a> <a href="/wiki/Popular_music" title="Popular music">popular music</a>. In the 2000s, multitracking software for computers such as <a href="/wiki/Pro_Tools" title="Pro Tools">Pro Tools</a> became widely used.</p>
